[6] Australia
Date: Tue 27 Feb 2018
Source: Honey Nine [edited]
https://honey.nine.com.au/2018/02/27/07/26/teacher-blasted-for-anti-vac-post


A teacher [from Victoria] has been slammed for seemingly supporting the spreading of measles among children. The teacher, who is a member of the Australia: Childcare for Unvaccinated Children Facebook page, was responding to a parent's post about measles when she made the controversial comment, the Herald Sun reports. The parent wrote, "With the recent measles outbreak near Dandenong [Melbourne], please contact/message me if your children get measles and you are happy to share." To which the private school teacher said, "Same plz!"

A measles outbreak has been reported in Melbourne's south east, with chief health officer Brett Sutton issuing a warning to the public. "The department is attempting to contact people who may have been in contact with the individual while they were infectious," he said.

Another measles outbreak has been reported in western Sydney, with 23 confirmed cases of measles in New South Wales.

The measles vaccine is free and the Australian Medical Association (AMA) recommends all children and adults have 2 doses of the vaccine during their lifetimes. AMA president Dr Michael Gannon says the federal government's "No Jab, No Pay" policy has led to 200 000 children being fully vaccinated but has asked doctors to do more to reach out to parents hesitant to vaccinate their kids.

Measles is a highly infectious viral disease that can have serious complications. Symptoms include fever, tiredness, runny nose, cough, and sore red eyes. These symptoms normally appear a few days before a red blotchy rash.

[byline: Jo Abi]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The parent and teacher were referring to the concept of "measles parties". At these gatherings, kids who haven't been immunized would be exposed to the disease so that they would become infected and thus "build up" immunity. It's similar to the idea behind "chickenpox parties", which were highly popular among parents before the pox vaccine was introduced in the United States in 1995.

But intentionally exposing your kids to measles -- a serious and highly contagious illness -- is harmful. Public health officials warned parents against the "natural infection" practice back in 2015, saying that the tactic unnecessarily places the exposed children at potentially grave risk and could contribute to further spread of the outbreak.

People with measles can be very sick for 7-10 days, with symptoms that include a high fever, cough, sore throat, and rash. And a small number of children who get measles develop severe complications from the disease, including brain infections that can cause permanent neurological damage. According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 1-2 children die from the disease for every 1000 who get it. The risk of severe disease following natural infection is much greater and more life threatening than anything that is seen following vaccination. - Mod.LK

